\section{The $H^0$ algebraic bridge}
\label{sec:HModule_zero}

After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} the cohomology groups $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ are well-defined and carry the canonical $\Module k$-structure inherited from \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule}. For Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, deferred), the next algebraic preliminary is the identification of the degree-zero piece $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$ with a Hom group: this is the bridge from sheaf cohomology to representable Hom-functors, and on a connected proper $k$-curve it eventually rewrites $H^0(C, \struct C)$ as $\Gamma(C, \struct C)$ viewed as a $k$-module.

The Lean implementation reuses Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} (file \lstinline{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/Linear.lean}), which provides
\[
  \Ext_R(X, Y, 0) \;\simeq_R\; (X \to Y)
\]
in any $\Linear R$-enriched abelian category for $R$ a commutative ring. Specialised to $R = k$ and to the $\Linear k$-enriched abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ (the $\Linear k$ enrichment is auto-inferable from \lstinline{HasSheafify} via \lstinline{Sheaf.linear}; this typeclass-level inference is verified by an iter-010 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe), the equivalence specialises to
\[
  \HModule\,k\,F\,0 \;\simeq_k\; \bigl((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k) \,\to\, F\bigr).
\]

\begin{definition}[$H^0$ as a $k$-linear Hom group]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category with $J : \mathrm{GrothendieckTopology}\,C$, and assume $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$ and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k))$. For $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, the $k$-linear equivalence
  \[
    \mathtt{HModule\_zero\_linearEquiv}_F \,:\, \HModule\,k\,F\,0 \;\simeq_k\; \bigl((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k) \to F\bigr)
  \]
  is given by \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}.
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule}
  Direct from \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} applied to the abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, which is $\Linear k$-enriched (auto-inferable from the prerequisites of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}) and has $\HasExt$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}). The $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev} reducibility of $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule}) lets instance synthesis unfold the wrapper to the underlying $\Ext$ group, and \lstinline{linearEquiv₀} returns the $\Module k$-linear bijection between that $\Ext$ group and the corresponding Hom group in the sheaf category. The closure body is therefore a one-liner \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}; iter-010 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe confirms the closure compiles end-to-end against current Mathlib.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Why \texttt{linearEquiv} and not \texttt{addEquiv} or \texttt{equiv}]
  Mathlib provides three flavours of the $\Ext^0 \simeq \Hom$ equivalence: \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.homEquiv₀} (plain $\simeq$), \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.addEquiv₀} (additive $\simeq^+$), \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} ($R$-linear $\simeq_R$). The iter-010 implementation chooses the strongest, \lstinline{linearEquiv₀}, because the $k$-linear refinement is the one consumed downstream: $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,0) \iff \Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\dots) \to F)$ via \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv}, which requires a $\Module k$-linear equivalence on its left side.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Why this bridge and not \texttt{HModule\_forget}]
  Session~15's \texttt{recommendations.md} proposed an alternative iter-010 polish lemma \lstinline{HModule_forget}: a simp lemma identifying the $\forget_2 (\ModuleCat\,k)\,\AddCommGrpCat$-image of $\HModule\,k\,F\,n$ with $\Sheaf.\mathtt H\,((\sheafCompose\,\_\,(\forget_2\,\dots)).\mathrm{obj}\,F)\,n$. Iter-010 plan-agent re-read of Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean} reveals that $\Sheaf.\mathtt H\,F\,n := \Ext\bigl((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)),\ F,\ n\bigr)$ — the unit object is $\ULift\,\mathbb Z$, whereas $\HModule$ uses $\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$. The two unit objects are unrelated under $\forget_2 (\ModuleCat\,k)\,\AddCommGrpCat$ (the former forgets to $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,k$, not $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)$). The two cohomology theories are related by a change-of-coefficient comparison map, but it is generically not an isomorphism — so \lstinline{HModule_forget} as proposed is not a \lstinline{rfl}/single-application closure. Iter-010 instead targets this $H^0$ bridge, which is genuinely a one-liner and is the algebraic fact downstream consumers actually need.
\end{remark}

